Our mission✨Include Disabled Kids✨ We want to see inclusive playground equipment at EVERY school!🛝 We’ve been making inclusive playground vids🎥 for quite a long time now and believe it or not, wheelchair swing is by far the MOST hated😡 But why⁉️.. Most popular statements include:🗣️ 1. “It’s too expensive!”💵 2. “The kids are just going to break it!” 3. “Someone is going to get hurt!”😢  4. “Why waste money on something only a small percentage of people can use?!”♿️ But then… 1. The wheelchair swing is not more expensive then many other non inclusive playground equipment options that are implemented on playgrounds all the time. Is it expense or allocation of funds that needs to be worked on? 🧐 2. Do we stop installing other playground equipment because it gets damaged, or just the accessible ones? 3. Yes someone may get hurt. Kids get hurt on playgrounds all the time. Want to know what piece of equipment has the most accidents❓The monkey bars!It will not be the wheelchair swing♿️ 4. And last but not least, here at The Recess Project Inc. we leave no child behind!✋We don’t care if there is only one student that could use this equipment, they deserve to play too📣 Also, many school playgrounds are used by the community outside of school hours. Accessible playground equipment is needed for caregivers with disabilities as well!💕 Disabled kids have a right to RECESS🏫 Inclusion benefits EVERYONE🌍 To help include kids with disabilities be included on the school playground please consider supporting The Recess Project Inc.🫶 🎥 @Discover with Dallas  #playgrounds #wheelchairaccessible #inclusion #wheelchair #therecessproject #disability #bethechange #wheelchairlife #wheelchairuser #inclusiveplayground

In all seriousness, Tylers diagnosis is extremely scary and real. We survive these times by laughing and continuing to try and make memories, even if it is in the walls of a hospital. His nurses find so much joy in his sense of humor and they adore how much he makes them laugh, even with how much hes going through. The past 5 months have been an emotional rollercoaster with many more lows than highs. We appreciate everybodys love and support throughout this time, and i will always encourage Tyler to keep his sense of humor. Cancer is extremely serious and not a joke. It comes out of nowhere and flips your life upside. Tell your people you love them and take nothing for granted. 💕 Please enjoy some of the highlights of Tylerbeing his silly goofy self. I’ll be lying in a pool of my own blood, know that the knife is in your hands- and still forgive you.  I will reason with myself, surmise that the knife just fell into your hands and you did not intend for it to make me bleed.  I will come up with every reason you may have had- justify your actions for you, heal myself- and move on.  I do not have time to wait for ‘closure’, and I do not have time to blame those who hurt me forever.  My blood will replenish and my wounds will close, and I’ll take the knife out of your hands before I ever let you hurt me that way again. ✨Five Signs of Self-Abandonment in Relationships✨ 1. Trying to manage your partner's feelings 2. Avoiding difficult topics 3. Sacrificing your boundaries to please or appease 4. Suppressing your emotions 5. Talking yourself out of and minimizing your own needs If any of these sound familiar, don't worry, it’s something you can start to work on at any time. And it’s human because our internal attachment systems can pull us toward keeping the peace and prioritizing our partner. The problem is that sometimes it goes too far when we sacrifice too much at the expense of our essential selves. Over the long term, this does not serve our relationships — with our partners or ourselves. It starts with paying attention and increasing awareness of your own feelings and behaviors. It starts with connecting more deeply to yourself. This is something you can begin to do at any time. After all, there is no more important relationship than the one you have with yourself. Happy Diwali! This year, I asked teachers if we could come into the boy’s classrooms to do a lesson on Diwali - celebrating the festival of light over darkness, goodness over evil. We read books, did a rangoli craft for second graders, set up centers in Dev’s pre school classroom, and enjoyed snacks and mango juice.  The teachers welcomed us in with open arms, and it was a moment of pride as Carter and Dev got to share something unique about our Indian culture and family traditions with their classmates. I’m sharing a FREE resource for you (head over to IG same handle!) with a detailed lesson plan and links to everything we used! At a time where many of us are losing our faith in humanity and feel a divide in our foundational beliefs of goodness over evil, this lesson felt appropriate and necessary. We have to keep doing the work to teach inclusivity and acceptance. It takes all of us.❤️ Peep the 🪔pajamas at the end!

Why did it actually look SO GOOD! 😳 backstory ::: Kay has craved so many things over the last 36 weeks, and while they are really random, they are always delicious! I do my best to get Kay whatever cravings that she is having, because I love seeing the excitement on her face when she finally gets to bite into something that she’s been wanting so bad! 😂 She came storming in with her brilliant idea! I’m sure she had been quietly thinking this up for the last hour and couldn’t hold it in anymore! 😂 She explained everything, and though it sounded weird, it actually sounded good! So I went and got the stuff and whipped it up for her. I think she liked it, based on her reaction! 😂 I am so glad that I can do simple things like this for Kay. She gets so excited and the look on her face always fills me with joy! We are nearing the end of her pregnancy, so idk how much longer she’ll have cravings like this. // LET’S ROLL⁠ •⁠ On September 11, 2001, Todd Beamer, a passenger on the hijacked United Airlines Flight 93, tried to place a call through an air phone, but was routed to a customer service representative instead, who passed him on to supervisor Lisa Jefferson. Beamer reported that one passenger had been killed and that a flight attendant had told him that both the pilot and co-pilot had been forced from the cockpit and may have been injured. He was also on the phone when the plane made a quick and violent turn. Later, he told the operator that he and some of the other passengers were planning to attack the hijackers and regain control of the aircraft, after they learned about what happened at the World Trade Center and The Pentagon. According to Jefferson, Beamer’s last audible words were “Are you ready? Okay. Let’s roll.”⁠ •⁠ The bravery demonstrated on this day is hard to comprehend. And we’ll never know how many people the small group of passengers on Flight 93 actually saved. Todd was among many others who showed terrific bravery on this terrible day in US history. Let us never forget these heroes, and let us strive to be as sacrificial as they were when the times comes.⁠ •⁠ #neverforget #staydangerous

Replying to @mkeydeez Sam Norton was described to me as a “fiercely loyal” and “the kind of friend you would always want in your corner because it meant you would be safe and cared for.” He took up running a few years ago and became devoted. He formed the Almost Friday Run Club and built a great community of fellow runners.  Tragically, Sam collapsed and lost his life on the 23rd mile of the Santa Rosa marathon this past August. Him and his friends had intended on crushing the Santa Rosa Marathon and doing their “victory lap” at the NYC marathon.  The rest is a direct quote from Sam’s friend, who is in the video and messaged me about his friend: “After that day, I really didn’t want to be a part of the race yesterday. I genuinely couldn’t imagine being out there without him. But his mom had asked us to take over Sam's bib (he was planning to run through the Herren Project, a cause that was deeply personal and meaningful to Sam as he lost his father in 2020 to substance abuse disorder in 2020).  While we agreed to run it for Sam, we wanted to turn it into a way we could honor and celebrate Sam. We coordinated with NYRR to get us a SAM bib and that was one of Sam’s favorite shirts, which we imagined he’d wear on raceday. All the signatures on the Bib are family and friends along the route, and the two of us ran with Sam from mile 23 onward to finish what he started.
No words can express the feelings at the finish line of the NYC Marathon. This was what I saw there between 2-3:30pm today.  Congrats to everyone who took part. #nyrr #nycmarathon

He couldn't see a way out of debt and the stress and pressure became too much. He ended up talking about his life with Officer Kevin Briggs for 92 minutes while he was on the edge of the bridge. "Somehow the compassion in his voice is what allowed me to kinda let my guard down enough for us to have a conversation,” Berthia would later say. 10 years later they met on the same bridge in much better circumstances. "The greater picture is that I need to be here for my daughter. You know, she's 10 now and, had you not been there, I wouldn't get to see her grow up,” Berthia told Briggs.

I spent 2 hours walking around in the blazing sun. It was my cousin’s birthday and she decided to go out for breakfast with a group of girls to get açaí bowls. I ate a breakfast protein bowl and an açaí bowl. I was the only one to get a meal with my açaí bowl, but even though I had two things to eat…I was still hungry. They all decided to walk around a bit and chat. After two hours of that…I was sweating, thirsty and hungry. So me and my mom decided to leave and go grocery shopping at Trader Joe’s. After grabbing what we needed, we both decided to go out and eat. As we were driving looking around, we came upon an Olive Garden. My mom reminds me of the stuffed pasta shells they have, and I immediately craved them. So we went and got a booth and looked over the menu. “Stuffed shells” were nowhere to be seen on the menu. My heart broke. I was excited over nothing. The waitress came up to see if we were ready to order (for some reason she gave off the weirdest vibe ever. idk if I was tripping) my mom asked her if they have stuffed shells. She said yes. I was throbbing in excitement. The waitress asked me what sauce I wanted. I got confused. Doesn’t it always come with marinara? Maybe they give options now so I just stuck with marinara.  “Do you wanna add a protein to it?”  This is where I was like woah. This dish just keeps getting better.  “You can do that?” I asked in pure confusion. She nodded her head so I asked for crispy chicken. She takes my mom’s order and walks away. I spend the next 10-15 minutes munching on breadsticks and salad just picturing how this meal is gonna come out. I wonder how will they plate this magnificent meal? I never had stuffed shells with all these accommodations. I was genuinely excited. I see the waitress coming to our table with a tray. Oh boy! My yummy special dish is coming! She sets the plate in front of me.  erm… it was nothing that I was expecting. She misunderstood and gave me shell shaped pasta with marinara and chicken. My high went to an all time low. Why on earth would I order this? No wonder why she was asking me what sauce and protein I wanted. Imagine if I said “just how it is☺️” when she asked me if I wanted to add anything. She would have brought out plain pasta.  However, no matter how bummed out I was when my dish came I did not speak up about it. My mom insisted, but I declined cause I just cannot physically say anything or inconvenience someone (even if it is not a big deal for them at all). I nibbled on my meal and took the rest to go. I blamed me not wanting to speak up on the waitress’s weird vibe I got, but deep down I’m just very socially awkward.  I just want stuffed shells. Someone let me know if they still have it, #stuffedshells #fyp #socialanxiety #olivegarden #foryou

My journey to PA school hasn’t been an easy one, but its been humbling to say the least. As a senior in highschool I use to shadow my PA mentor on the weekends. I hadn’t even graduated high school yet. Then in college I was so focused on academics I neglected my PCE. Just this year I went from having 0 PCE to over 1,000 hrs of PCE in just a short span of time.  Last cycle, I took the GRE TWICE and scored low. I had studied the whole summer. I cried in the testing center parking lot for 30 mins. No lie. Talk about a silent car ride home.. oh it was SILENT😂. Then, I found out most programs didn’t accept 2 of my science credits so that limited the number of programs I could apply to. I could literally only apply to 1 place and I didn’t get in. That just about sent me over the edge🥴. I retook 2 important chemistries my senior year of college and it almost broke me, but I didn’t give up.  I worked 2 jobs simultaneously to double my experience and was taking 17 credit hours when I really only had to take 13 my senior year. Most days I cried to my mom &  mentors.. but I didn’t quit. I never lost sight of the goal.  So this acceptance is VERYYYYY personal and deserving for me. It still feels surreal for me honestly, but I’m grateful that it’s finally happening. I KNOW the real work starts now, but I’m still enjoying my moment 🩺🫶🏾.  #acceprance #paschool #paschooljourney #gradschool

Replying to @username tdlr; Yale is the the least stressful med school experience possible. While all med schools learn the same material, the learning experience can have enormous implications for your residency application, ability engage in things like research or study for boards, and your mental health and happiness. How does Yale accomplish this? NO preclinical grades, no class rank, no shelf exams for clinicals and only P/F for clerkships, annonymous exams, we get up to 12 weeks of study time for the boards, tuition free optional 5th year for extra time to do research, other degrees and/or study for boards, collaborative students because no competition, great faculty to student ratio. However if you are someone who needs external factors to motivate you, Yale may not be the right place and most people use the extra time and flexibility to do things like run programs/organizations/iniatives, do research, and overall do things that they are passionate in that contribute to the healthcare ecosystem. #yale #medschool #clinical #med #medstudent #grades #usmle #dmiyagi #drmiyagi #medic #medtok #dmiyagimedmentor #greenscreen

I was the only Nay on the Ohio House Resolution on Israel. It was not an easy decision to make. No one wants to vote against a resolution condemning violence. But this resolution fell short of what it should have been. To condemn terror but to not ignore the damage and destruction endured by the Palestinian people.  I could not vote ‘Yes’ and abandon my Palestinian friends and neighbors who for too long had very few stand for them.  I still strongly pray for the Jewish lives lost and mourn with my Jewish friends and neighbors as they live through this devastating moment.   But as my friend Rep Isaacsohn stated: It is not moral equivalence to mourn the loss of all innocent lives including those in Gaza.  I cannot in good conscience sit here and vote yes on a resolution that does not ask for a de-escalation of violent retribution launched by Israel against largely civilian territory. The Palestinian children also deserve someone to stand up for them and condemn their murder. Those babies who right now are denied water, electricity and medicine, deserve to have someone stand up for them and condemn their abuse. An abuse they have suffered for over 75 years. With over 6,000 palestinian lives lost since 2008 and thousands more injured and displaced It is time to call for true justice and apply the values of universal human rights to all victims of oppression, regardless of nationality, religion or skin color.  I send my prayers for peace and the protection of innocent lives lost during this conflict. Be it Palestinian, Jewish, American or any other loss of life.  Israeli writer Gideon Levy stated: “We now have to cry bitterly for the Israeli victims, but we should also cry for Gaza" And finally to quote my favorite verse in the Quran: “O you who believe, be upholders of justice - witnesses for God, even though against (the interest of) yourselves or your parents, and kinsmen.” 4:135 #freepalestine

I saw my final 7th world wonder and I might’ve cried a little 🥹 If I’ve learned anything in life, it’s to go after the things that make you feel alive & set your soul on fire. And don’t stop until you’ve had enough! ❤️‍🔥 I remember graduating college and everyone telling me how proud they were and what an accomplishment it was.  But on the inside, I felt so normal. I thought ‘wow, this is anticlimactic’. So I started to travel because that was the only thing I truly wanted to do & could imagine myself doing as a new graduate 🗺️ & it changed my life. I stopped living for other people or for what was expected of me and I started living for MYSELF ✨ Flying in a helicopter over such a beautiful part of the world while getting to check off the last wonder on my list, left me feeling an immense gratitude and happiness for the life that I’ve created. More than graduating college ever did.  I read somewhere that only less than 5% of the population ever gets to see all 7 New World Wonders so I’m feeling extra special about this 🥹 So follow your dreams, guys 🫶🏼 there’s no better feeling than accomplishing them!  #7worldwonders #finalworldwonder #sevenwondersoftheworld #christtheredeemer

Here's a couple of the many things you could do, rather than scrolling through SHEIN or Amazon, or making that late night Walmart and Mcdonald's run if you're trying to save money! I hope you enjoy this <3 1. Take a Nap. This is probably the easiest, most simple thing you could do. It makes time pass by so much more quickly so you don't get those constant intrusive thoughts that'll cost you $20! Plus, if you've got a history of a bad sleep schedule this would be your opportunity to grab a couple more hours of sleep. 2. Try Yoga. I personally have just started practicing yoga and I feel like it helps me a lot. I get to wind down, calm my mind, and stretch my body out. I don't know about you, but I sleep in some funky positions that leave me cramped up. So doing a few stretches throughout the days really helps with those cramps and is a great alternative to working out (which I hate to do!!). 3. Try a New Recipe. Baking is one of my favorite things to do with friends. You don't even have to do any of these alone! If you have the basic necessities, you could bake or cook a lot of things at home. Try that frozen chocolate strawberry recipe off TikTok. Or if you're brave enough, try a professional chef tutorial on YouTube just for fun! 4. Clean Up Your Nails. I'm very picky about keeping my nails pretty and clean so it prevents me from wanting to pick at them as an old habit. You can paint your nails a pretty color, or just simply file them down a bit and clean up your cuticles. If you're a perfectionist like me, this will keep you occupied for quite some time. 5. Organize. I have a few drawers in my bedroom that I tend to just throw the most random things into, so I like to go through it every once and a while and I find some pretty crazy things. Clean up your desk, go through your bookshelf, or organize your clothes. Whatever you've been putting off, try it now. 6. Teach A Pet A Trick. Grab some treats and show your dog how to roll over, dance in a circle, or give a high five. If you're a cat person, there's a way to teach your cat how to give you a high five :) 7. Watch Something. Find a documentary on Netflix that's trending, or ask a friend for a movie recommendation. I have about 5 different tv shows I'm in the middle of watching, so if you have that habit then make it a goal to finish one of them! 8. Dance!! This is a great opportunity to just let yourself lose and calm down, and even find a few new songs that pique your interests. Turn on some 2000s party songs and dance around your room while you get a couple side tasks done! #lemon8diary #savemoney #thingstodo #bored #funwithfriends #lemon8us #lemon8 Follow @mariahnichole0 on Lemon8 for more!

This month marks 20 years since one of the most impactful moments of my life when a shark took my arm while on a surfing off the coast of Kauai, my birth place. Many people could look at the incident back in 2003 as a major setback for me, but God had so much in store for the future!  It's absolutely wild to think how my life started and where it is now and all the amazing yet challenging things in between. I didn't wake up in the hospital thinking I was invincible and was gonna get back to surfing. After getting a hint of inspiration,  I had to dream it up, flip my mindset and be willing to do what I had not seen anyone else do.  And I am so glad I was willing to try and give it my best shot! Now I get to surf with my two eldest sons Tobias and Wesley and my hubby! I get to enjoy these sweet moments with my newborn daughter. There is so much to be grateful for, and these past 20 years have been filled with incredible moments and huge overcoming seasons. When you have your “Shark Attack” moments in life. I hope you're willing to try, and give life your best shot! You too CAN OVERCOME!
